}} The 'Austrian Football Bundesliga' () is the highest-ranking national league
club competition in Austrian football. It is the competition which decides the
Austrian national football champions, as well the country's entrants for the
various European cups run by UEFA. Since Austria climbed from nineteenth to
fifteenth place in the UEFA association coefficient rankings at the end of the
2011â12 season, the league gained its second spot for the UEFA
Champions League.

The Austrian Bundesliga, which began in the 1974â75 season, has been a separate
registered association since 1 December 1991. It has been most won by the two
Viennese giants FK Austria Wien, who were national champions 23 times, and SK
Rapid Wien, who won the national title 32 times. At present it is composed of
two divisions â the Bundesliga and First League, known as "tipp3-Bundesliga
powered by T-Mobile" and "Heute fÃ¼r Morgen Erste Liga" for sponsorship reasons.
